title: The Documentation Generator
content:
The Documentation Generator

This turned my undocumented mess into something my team actually understands.

Better than any developer I've worked with.

---

<documentation_task>
Create production-ready documentation for this codebase
</documentation_task>

<code_context>
<codebase>
[Paste key files: main logic, API routes, complex algorithms]
</codebase>

<project_info>
- Project name: [name]
- Purpose: [what does this solve?]
- Target users: [who uses this?]
- Tech stack: [technologies]
</project_info>
</code_context>

<documentation_requirements>
<readme_structure>
1. Project overview (one paragraph - what and why)
2. Features (bullet points - what it does)
3. Installation (step-by-step - how to set up)
4. Configuration (environment variables, settings)
5. Usage examples (actual code samples)
6. API documentation (if applicable)
7. Architecture overview (how it works)
8. Contributing guidelines (how to help)
9. Troubleshooting (common issues)
</readme_structure>

<code_comments>
- Add inline comments for complex logic
- Explain WHY not WHAT (code shows what)
- Document function parameters and return values
- Add examples for non-obvious usage
</code_comments>

<api_documentation>
For each endpoint:
- Purpose
- Authentication requirements
- Request format (with example)
- Response format (with example)
- Error responses (with status codes)
- Rate limits
</api_documentation>
</documentation_requirements>

<audience_considerations>
Write for:
- New team members (onboarding in 1 hour)
- Future you (6 months later)
- Open source contributors (if applicable)
</audience_considerations>

<output_format>
1. Complete README. md
2. Inline code documentation
3. API. md (if applicable)
4. CONTRIBUTING. md (if open source)
5. Architecture diagram description (in text/markdown)
</output_format>

<quality_standards>
- Use clear, simple language (no jargon without explanation)
- Include real working examples
- Keep it up-to-date (no outdated screenshots or commands)
- Make it scannable (headers, bullets, code blocks)
</quality_standards>
</documentation_task>
